TY  - JOUR
T1  - SSB and Weighted Linear Utility As Expected Utility with Suspicion
AU  - Bordley, Robert
AU  - Hazen, Gordon B.
Y1  - 1991/04/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.37.4.396
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.37.4.396
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 396
EP  - 408
VL  - 37
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We show that a ?suspicious? subjective expected utility (SEU) maximizer, i.e., one who treats potential consequences of states as information useful in assessing the probability of those states, may under reasonable circumstances act as though he were maximizing either weighted linear utility, or skew-symmetric bilinear (SSB) utility. SEU with suspicion, therefore, explains at least as many empirical violations of SEU theory as do these and similar models. We give examples to illustrate how several important types of SEU violations may seem to arise when suspicion is present.
AB  - We show that a ?suspicious? subjective expected utility (SEU) maximizer, i.e., one who treats potential consequences of states as information useful in assessing the probability of those states, may under reasonable circumstances act as though he were maximizing either weighted linear utility, or skew-symmetric bilinear (SSB) utility. SEU with suspicion, therefore, explains at least as many empirical violations of SEU theory as do these and similar models. We give examples to illustrate how several important types of SEU violations may seem to arise when suspicion is present.
