TY  - JOUR
T1  - Variance Effects in Cyclic Production Systems
AU  - Sarkar, Debashish
AU  - Zangwill, Willard I.
Y1  - 1991/04/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.37.4.444
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.37.4.444
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 444
EP  - 453
VL  - 37
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Utilizing a cyclic queue system, this paper investigates the effect of variance on a multi-item production facility. The variance of setup time, service rate and arrival rate is shown to have a powerful and sometimes paradoxical influence. Reduction in setup time, for example, is usually presumed to reduce inventory. We demonstrate that inventory can blow up if setup time is cut. Another paradoxical effect of variance is on processing rate. Speeding up the processing rate should reduce the material waiting to be processed. Again we show that the opposite can hold. Other properties of variance are examined, such as its relationship to KAIZEN and Just-In-Time production practices, and especially its property of impairing capacity.
AB  - Utilizing a cyclic queue system, this paper investigates the effect of variance on a multi-item production facility. The variance of setup time, service rate and arrival rate is shown to have a powerful and sometimes paradoxical influence. Reduction in setup time, for example, is usually presumed to reduce inventory. We demonstrate that inventory can blow up if setup time is cut. Another paradoxical effect of variance is on processing rate. Speeding up the processing rate should reduce the material waiting to be processed. Again we show that the opposite can hold. Other properties of variance are examined, such as its relationship to KAIZEN and Just-In-Time production practices, and especially its property of impairing capacity.
